e propulsion unit alone, with no &quot;fuel&quot; or structure is something like 360000kg. While a Sea Dragon could do this, a HLV this size is unlikly to be built anytime in the near future, unfortunately. The 10-m's dry weight is only 91000kg, so could be done with planned or existing HLVs in the near future. Improving the efficiency of the smaller unit keeps expensive launches down. And it is a better reference to other propulsion systems which usually are scaled up to a 10-m vehicle size(to be used with a Mars mission), but no further. The pulse units yields (a nominal 1kt in the GA-5009 study) could be easily reduced for tests.<br>
<br>
Remember the picture of the 20-m you have in the Preserve would take over 13 Sea Dragon-class HLVs to put it in orbit as loaded.<br>
<br>
And the pulse units were conservatively planned to use 2kg of plutonium each, 1kg should work, meaning a vehicle making a 64km/s total mission velocity trip, would only need 1200kg of Pu for fuel. The physics package destroyed the case preventing all the mass and energy to be directed. As I said, Ted Taylor didn't know if it was possible to have that much direction, and he did lots of work on rad case directional bombs, but he did think it could be done in the future(i.e now). An improved case would definitely be needed. <p>"If," he wispered, "if we could only pick that lock...." - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 986<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/7/02 10:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Improving 10-m ORION</span><hr size=1> 1.2 tonnes of Pu239 is an ENORMOUS amount!<br>
-----<br>
<br>
Yes, the explosion destroys the case, but the X-rays move at &quot;c&quot;, incredibly faster than the rest of the explosion. The radiation channel should be intact for the duration of the energy transfer. <br>
-------<br>
<br>
A 1 kg core require a LARGE amount of explosives. It may conserve on Pu, but it appears to be a major ramp-up in mass.<br>
----------<br>
<br>
yale<br>
