<br>
Admittedly 1.2 tonnes of Pu is a lot, but easily achievable considering the masses available from recycled weapons, reprocessed fuel, and stockpiled amounts (The Russians had enough stockpiled in the early 1990's to build another 10000 bombs, along with enough HEU to make an additional 30000). The material is out there already.<br>
<br>
I am not an expert like Taylor was, I am only saying if it was that simple to do, someone at LANL or GA would have figured it out by then. You are right, the radiation case is optically thick enough to contain the radiation until the energy is released, but not the mass. The important thing is to redirect more of the unit's total mass at the pusher. This requires lightening the elements which are not directed at the pusher and directing more of the explosion's mass towards the pusher, both of which is easier said then done. The radiation case is not strong enough to survive long enough to propel all of the expanding gas and plasma out the channel, hopefully it can be made so to expel most of it. Using a greater percentage of the unit's mass for propulsion causes the increase in Isp. <p>"If," he wispered, "if we could only pick that lock...." - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 992<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/7/02 9:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Improving 10-m ORION</span><hr size=1> I agree that there is a heck of a lot of Pu239 out there!<br>
